      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Westbeth, a Canvas Still Taking Shape'' (May 25): I have lived in Westbeth from the beginning, 30 years ago, and remember Richard Meier's beautiful colors in the hallways. The colors have been wiped out and replaced with bland white and gray. This poem was written in memory of Richard Meier's colors:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Westbeth, a Canvas Still Taking Shape'' (May 25): I have lived in Westbeth from the beginning, 30 years ago, and remember Richard Meier's beautiful colors in the hallways. The colors have been wiped out and replaced with bland white and gray. This poem was written in memory of Richard Meier's colors:</p>
        <p>THE HALLWAY</p>
        <p>All clean, uniform and devoid of color</p>
        <p>Is Westbeth now a hospital, mental institution</p>
        <p>or a bland nightmare --</p>
        <p>What happened to the creative colors?</p>
        <p>Was it wiped out by the nonartists?</p>
        <p>Bring back creativity.</p>
        <p>Is the blandness a symbol of lost art?</p>
        <p>Can we find our way back?</p>
        <p>EDITH STEPHEN  New York</p>
      </block>
